      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Rest the dough",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Combine the semolina, flour, icing sugar, and mahlab (if using) in a large bowl. Pour the lukewarm melted butter over and work through with your fingers until the mixture resembles damp sand. Cover and leave to rest for at least 1 hour at room temperature.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the fillings",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "For the date filling: process the pitted dates, butter, cinnamon, and cardamom in a food processor until a smooth paste forms. If without a processor, knead together by hand until uniform. For the pistachio filling: combine the ground pistachios, icing sugar, and rose water and work together until the mixture holds when pressed.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Finish the dough",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "After resting, add the rose water and milk to the semolina mixture and bring together into a soft, pliable dough. It should hold its shape when pressed but not be sticky. If it crumbles, add more milk a teaspoon at a time.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Shape and fill",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Preheat the oven to 170°C conventional (150°C fan). Pinch off a piece of dough the size of a walnut (about 25 g). Roll into a ball and press your thumb into the centre to form a deep cup. Place a teaspoon of filling inside, close the dough over the top and roll between your palms to seal. If using a maamoul mould, press the filled ball into the mould and tap out. Otherwise, flatten slightly and mark with fork tines. Place on ungreased baking trays, spaced 3 cm apart.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bake and finish",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bake for 18 to 22 minutes until the bases are pale gold and the top is set but still light in colour. Do not overbake, maamoul are dry and hard if overcooked. Cool completely on the tray. Dust heavily with icing sugar before serving.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
